Enhances cache management and workflow summary reporting

Implements cache cleanup logic to remove old entries from previous executions, ensuring only current session cache is utilized. Introduces methods for clearing the cache and retrieving cache statistics, improving monitoring capabilities. Updates the AutomatedWorkflow to print a summary of processing statistics upon completion, including cache information. Additionally, refines logging for better tracking of cache operations and workflow outcomes.

Enhances GIF settings and cache validation in automated workflow

Updates gif_settings.yaml to allow automatic height calculation for better aspect ratio preservation. Implements cache validation logic in the AutomatedWorkflow to clean up invalid cache entries, improving cache management and ensuring only valid outputs are retained. Adds CLI support for cache validation, providing users with feedback on cache status and cleaned entries. Refines logging for better tracking of cache operations and workflow outcomes.

Enhances GIF segmentation and multiprocessing capabilities

Updates gif_settings.yaml to introduce multiprocessing configuration options, allowing for dynamic analysis of optimal worker counts based on system capabilities. Refines the AutomatedWorkflow and GifGenerator classes to utilize the new multiprocessing settings, improving parallel processing efficiency during GIF segment creation. Implements a method for calculating optimal segmentation workers, enhancing performance based on hardware and system load. Additionally, updates logging to provide detailed feedback on worker utilization and segment processing progress.

Enhances GIF validation and summary generation in automated workflow

Introduces a fast GIF validation method to improve performance during GIF processing, allowing for quicker checks without full frame iteration. Updates the AutomatedWorkflow and VideoSegmenter classes to utilize this new validation method, enhancing efficiency in GIF segment handling. Additionally, implements comprehensive summary generation for segments, providing detailed insights into MP4 and GIF files, including size, duration, and frame count. Refines logging to improve tracking of summary creation and validation processes.

Add crop detection settings to GIF configuration and enhance crop validation logic

Introduces crop detection configuration in gif_settings.yaml, allowing users to enable or disable crop detection and set thresholds for significant cropping. Updates the GifGenerator class to respect these settings, ensuring that crop suggestions are only applied when they exceed defined border thresholds. This enhancement aims to prevent unintended cropping and improve the overall quality of generated GIFs.

Update GIF settings and enhance logging in automated workflow

Increased the maximum file size limit for GIF uploads in gif_settings.yaml from 8MB to 10MB to align with Discord's updated limits for free users. Improved logging in the AutomatedWorkflow class by implementing a safe filename method for better handling of Unicode characters in log messages. Additionally, refined file sorting logic to prioritize files based on creation time, enhancing the efficiency of file processing.

Original issue description:

> @copilot
> 
> ⸻
> 
> Summary
> 
> The NOEMI Survey App needs a full sync to the updated docs/noemi-survey-config.json, a UI polish pass to meet brand requirements (luxury, elegance, sophistication, mobile-first), a working tutorial flow in the swipe game, and database repairs: several .sql files do not run cleanly, and the runtime schema is out of sync with the app’s expectations. Update tests accordingly.
> 
> ⸻
> 
> Goals
> 	•	Render exactly what the updated JSON specifies (survey + game tutorial).
> 	•	Make the survey UI consistent, refined, and mobile-first.
> 	•	Ensure all migrations run safely on a fresh Supabase DB.
> 	•	Bring live schema into alignment with supabase/expected-schema.sql.
> 	•	Update unit/E2E tests to reflect the new copy and flows.
> 
> ⸻
> 
> Scope of Work (Checklists)
> 
> 1) Survey UI & Copy
> 	•	Sync all copy to docs/noemi-survey-config.json.
> 	•	Replace “How do you identify?” → “What is your gender?”.
> 	•	Remove “ritual” language across title, subtitle, prompts, options.
> 	•	Ensure app uses JSON as source-of-truth (no stale strings in code).
> 	•	Tighten spacing & type scale (mobile-first) in src/index.css.
> 	•	Reduce headline sizes (h1, .group-title) using clamp(...).
> 	•	Use tighter vertical rhythm: prefer var(--space-2|3) within question blocks and --space-4 between blocks.
> 	•	Keep lines at ~65–75ch width where applicable; maintain max-width caps.
> 	•	Standardize input widths (notably Q1) via reusable classes in src/index.css:
> 	•	.survey-input, .survey-select, .survey-textarea → width: 100%, max-width: 560px, box-sizing: border-box.
> 	•	Apply to all inputs/selects/textareas in src/components/Survey.jsx.
> 	•	Eliminate fragile selectors that cause style bleed:
> 	•	Replace .survey-wrapper .stack:first-child with a named container class (e.g., .progress-summary) and update markup in Survey.jsx.
> 	•	Modularize question rendering in Survey.jsx:
> 	•	Extract SingleSelectQuestion, MultiSelectQuestion, ScaleQuestion, etc., for consistency and easier styling.
> 	•	Welcome screen cleanup in src/components/App.jsx:
> 	•	Ensure survey.meta.title, subtitle, and CTA reflect JSON.
> 	•	Remove mystical “ritual” phrasing.
> 	•	A11y:
> 	•	Every control has a <label htmlFor>.
> 	•	Focus rings visible and tasteful.
> 	•	Click/tap targets ≥ 40px.
> 
> Acceptance (UI):
> 	•	Headings reduced and consistent.
> 	•	No styling bleed from :first-child.
> 	•	Inputs full-width on mobile; capped on larger screens.
> 	•	All copy reflects JSON updates.
> 	•	Axe audit has no new violations.
> 
> ⸻
> 
> 2) Swipe Game & Tutorial
> 	•	Tutorial cards: read tutorial sequence defined at the bottom of docs/noemi-survey-config.json and present it before the game starts.
> 	•	Replace the hard-coded sequence in src/hooks/useSwipeGame.js with JSON-driven content.
> 	•	Support “Next / Start” CTAs.
> 	•	Persist tutorial state:
> 	•	Store a “tutorial seen” flag in localStorage.
> 	•	Add “View tutorial” link within game UI to replay.
> 	•	Game polish:
> 	•	Align button and deck spacing with tightened tokens.
> 	•	Confirm arrow keys map correctly (Right=Like, Left=Dislike, Up=Love, Down=Unsure).
> 	•	Maintain focus management after swipe.
> 	•	Copy cleanup:
> 	•	Remove “ritual” language from tooltips, headings, helper text.
> 
> Acceptance (Game):
> 	•	JSON tutorial displays on first run, can be replayed, and is skippable.
> 	•	Keyboard and touch swipes work; instant visual feedback remains.
> 	•	Game UI respects new spacing and type scale.
> 
> ⸻
> 
> 3) Database & SQL (Supabase / Postgres)
> 
> Problem: Some .sql files fail; app expects tables/columns/policies that may not exist or differ in production. Must repair with safe, additive migrations.
> 	•	BEST TO DELETE EVERYTHING AND START FROM SCRATCH (DROP ALL TABLES AND BEGIN FRESH WITH NEW SUPABASE DEPLOY INSTRUCTIONS)
> 	•	Save the report as a GitHub Actions artifact and paste a summary in this issue.
> 	•	If no DB URL is supplied, at least validate expected schema syntax (script supports this).
> 	•	Migrations must apply cleanly on a fresh DB:
> 	•	supabase/migrations/0001_init.sql (baseline)
> 	•	supabase/migrations/0002_add_design_tables.sql (design tables, safe column adds, indexes, RLS)
> 	•	supabase/migrations/0003_fix_participants_rls_policies.sql (RLS fixes for participants and swipes)
> 	•	If any fail, add new NNNN_description.sql migrations that only use:
> 	•	CREATE TABLE IF NOT EXISTS
> 	•	ALTER TABLE … ADD COLUMN with existence checks
> 	•	CREATE INDEX IF NOT EXISTS
> 	•	DROP POLICY IF EXISTS + CREATE POLICY
> 	•	No destructive operations; never drop/alter types on live data without a dedicated migration plan & manual approval.
> 	•	Align to supabase/expected-schema.sql:
> 	•	Ensure participants includes: email, marketing_opt_in, answers jsonb, location_data jsonb, is_complete boolean, progress text, created_at, updated_at.
> 	•	Ensure design_sets, designs, swipes exist with required indexes and RLS.
> 	•	RLS policies:
> 	•	anon can INSERT into participants and swipes and SELECT them for analytics.
> 	•	anon can SELECT design_sets and designs.
> 	•	authenticated has full access for admin operations.
> 	•	Verify with a policy existence check (see 0003 approach); add verification DO $$ blocks if needed.
> 	•	Seeds / static content:
> 	•	Confirm /public/designs/index.json exists and is current.
> 	•	Confirm any generator script (e.g., scripts/split_quadrants.py) outputs the structure the game expects.
> 	•	DB health banner (src/components/DbHealthBanner.jsx):
> 	•	Ensure checkDbHealth validates new tables and surfaces helpful diagnostics.
> 	•	Improve copy and add a “copy diagnostics” success state.
> 
> Acceptance (DB):
> 	•	Fresh Supabase DB applies all migrations without error.
> 	•	check-schema-drift.sh reports no drift against expected-schema.sql.
> 	•	Anonymous survey submissions and swipes work end-to-end.
> 	•	Policies verified present; CI job captures a drift report artifact.
> 
> ⸻
> 
> 4) Tests
> 	•	Unit / component (Vitest + RTL):
> 	•	Update label queries to match new copy (e.g., Gender question).
> 	•	Ensure each question type has a rendering & interaction test.
> 	•	Add tests that ensure no styling bleed (first option unaffected).
> 	•	E2E (Playwright):
> 	•	Welcome → Survey → Game happy path.
> 	•	Tutorial appears on first play, can be skipped/replayed.
> 	•	Keyboard and swipe inputs recorded to Supabase (mock if needed).
> 	•	Visual expectations for spacing/headings at mobile widths.
> 	•	DB validations (mocked):
> 	•	Test schema drift script wrapper or a small Node wrapper that asserts non-empty diff triggers a failure state in CI.
> 	•	Snapshots / visual:
> 	•	Re-record when UI changes are intentional.
> 	•	Add minimal visual checks for type scale and spacing changes.
> 
> Acceptance (Tests):
> 	•	All tests green locally and in CI.
> 	•	Coverage includes at least one flow per question type and the tutorial path.
> 
> ⸻
> 
> 5) Misc Codebase Hygiene
> 	•	Services & utils: Review supabaseClient.js, analytics.js, geolocation.js for robust error handling and logging.
> 	•	Docs:
> 	•	README.md: update usage, dev modes (?dev=true, ?play=true), tutorial mention.
> 	•	AGENTS.md: reflect modular components and CSS token usage.
> 	•	Add comments to docs/noemi-survey-config.json describing fields and constraints.
> 	•	Env & examples:
> 	•	Add .env.example with VITE_SUPABASE_URL, VITE_SUPABASE_ANON_KEY, and any required flags.
> 	•	Add a quickstart section for local DB testing with Supabase CLI.
> 	•	CI pipeline:
> 	•	Ensure CI runs: pnpm install, pnpm lint, pnpm test, pnpm test:e2e, pnpm build, scripts/check-schema-drift.sh.
> 	•	Upload schema drift report as artifact on failure.
> 	•	Perf & a11y:
> 	•	Image preloading in the game is already implemented; validate that it doesn’t block input.
> 	•	Recheck keyboard nav and screen reader labels across survey and game.
> 
> ⸻
> 
> How to Reproduce (Current Issues)
> 	1.	Copy mismatch: Launch app and observe any text not matching docs/noemi-survey-config.json (gender prompt, ritual wording).
> 	2.	Style bleed: Inspect first items in answer lists; confirm no unintended styles caused by :first-child.
> 	3.	Input widths: Q1 sub-questions should not have inconsistent widths on mobile and desktop.
> 	4.	Tutorial: Game should show JSON-driven tutorial; currently the sequence may be hard-coded in useSwipeGame.js.
> 	5.	DB failures: Apply migrations to a fresh Supabase instance; note any errors or missing policies/tables.
> 
> ⸻
> 
> Proposed Implementation Notes
> 	•	Keep all database changes non-destructive; if breaking changes are required, open a separate PR with a data-safe plan.
> 	•	Encapsulate styles using CSS custom properties and named classes; avoid global selectors that target structural positions.
> 	•	Read tutorial config from JSON, not code, to prevent drift.
> 	•	Put all copy behind JSON to avoid stale strings in JSX.
> 
> ⸻
> 
> Commands
> 
> # Install & run
> pnpm install
> pnpm dev
> 
> # Lint / typecheck / tests
> pnpm lint
> pnpm test
> pnpm test:e2e
> pnpm build
>

> ./scripts/check-schema-drift.sh
> 
> # (Dev-only) Reset DB
> # supabase db reset
> 
> 
> ⸻
> 
> Definition of Done
> 	•	No copy mismatches; all text is JSON-driven.
> 	•	UI spacing/type standardized; inputs consistent; no style bleed.
> 	•	Tutorial is JSON-driven, persists “seen” state, and is replayable.
> 	•	All migrations apply cleanly; schema drift check passes.
> 	•	Unit/E2E tests updated and passing; CI green.
> 
> ⸻
> 
> If anything blocks progress (e.g., missing Supabase credentials), post diagnostics in this issue and PR and proceed with mocked paths where possible.

type.name: Feature
type.description: A request, idea, or new functionality

issue.body:
### Terms

- [X] I have searched [open and closed feature requests](https://github.com/scribe-org/Scribe-Data/issues?q=is%3Aissue+label%3Afeature)
- [X] I agree to follow Scribe-Data's [Code of Conduct](https://github.com/scribe-org/Scribe-Data/blob/main/.github/CODE_OF_CONDUCT.md)

### Description

This issue deals with adding data to [Wikidata](https://www.wikidata.org/) that could indicate which nouns in Spanish switch their articles to avoid difficult pronunciations. An example: agua (water) is feminine, but it's "el agua" to avoid "la agua" (but still "las aguas").

It would be convenient if [Wikidata](https://www.wikidata.org/) would also have a widely used article property such that nouns that have articles that don't match their gender could be indicated when they're annotated. This could be as simple as putting the correct article in the gender annotation.
